<subSubSection id="66ED838DFFEEFFEFFF3CF941C4E6F859" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" type="description">
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFF3CF941C763F912" blockId="10.[166,778,1681,2091]" box="[168,308,1681,1705]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<figureCitation id="B6CCCC83FFEEFFEFFF3CF941C763F912" box="[168,308,1681,1705]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="11.[168,231,987,1007]" captionTargetBox="[168,778,160,962]" captionTargetId="figure-693@11.[168,778,160,962]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 7. Birds of Bogotá’s Savannah. A. Lesbia nuna male, B. Buteo platypterus. C. Migratory flock of B. platypterus and B. swainsoni. D. Falco peregrinus. E–H. Asio flammeus bogotensis. E. Adult. F. Chicks and egg.G. Chick. H. Immature." pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Figure 7B, C</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFF3CF968C4CFF8EC" blockId="10.[166,778,1681,2091]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFF3CF968C76AF96B" bold="true" box="[168,317,1720,1744]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">New records.</emphasis>
About 1,500 individuals were recorded in a boreal migration flying above the ESNR and PJDNR on 
<date id="5A49F6C6FFEEFFEFFD6FF90AC748F8A8" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" value="2018-04-07">7 April 2018</date>
. The flock included 
<taxonomicName id="E9F7AB85FFEEFFEFFE6FF92CC4EBF8A8" authorityName="Vieillot" authorityYear="1823" box="[507,700,1787,1811]" class="Aves" family="Accipitridae" genus="Buteo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Accipitriformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="platypterus">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFE6FF92CC4EBF8A8" box="[507,700,1787,1811]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Buteo platypterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E9F7AB85FFEEFFEFFD67F92CC786F88E" authority="Bonaparte, 1838" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1838" class="Aves" family="Accipitridae" genus="Buteo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Accipitriformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="swainsoni">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFD67F92CC743F88E" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">B. swainsoni</emphasis>
Bonaparte, 1838
</taxonomicName>
. We recorded this species in systematic surveys in November of each year.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFF3CF8B5C4E6F859" blockId="10.[166,778,1681,2091]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFF3CF8B5C71DF8C6" bold="true" box="[168,330,1893,1917]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Identification.</emphasis>
Adult and immature individuals show differences in plumage. Adults have dark brown on the dorsum and barred chest. Immatures are similar on dorsum, but the chest is whitish with brown stripes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66ED838DFFEEFFEFFF3CF821C418F790" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFF3CF821C418F790" blockId="10.[166,778,1681,2091]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFF3CF821C74FF7B2" bold="true" box="[168,280,2033,2057]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Remarks.</emphasis>
We did not record any reproductive events. This species is a boreal migratory bird.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66ED838DFFEEFFEFFCBEFAFDC29AF9CE" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFCBEFAFDC223FA33" blockId="10.[810,1420,1325,1416]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFCBEFAFDC5E9FAFE" bold="true" box="[810,958,1325,1349]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="56E09096FFEEFFEFFC53FAFDC5A9FAFE" box="[967,1022,1325,1349]" name="United States of America" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">USA</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="56E09096FFEEFFEFFB9FFAFDC237FAFE" box="[1035,1120,1325,1349]" name="Canada" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Canada</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="56E09096FFEEFFEFFBF9FAFDC296FAFE" box="[1133,1217,1325,1349]" name="Mexico" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, Central America, northwestern South America to western 
<collectingCountry id="56E09096FFEEFFEFFB6DFA9EC302FADD" box="[1273,1365,1358,1382]" name="Ecuador" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="56E09096FFEEFFEFFAF1FA9FC50AFA33" name="Bolivia" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, and northwestern 
<collectingCountry id="56E09096FFEEFFEFFBBEFAA0C227FA33" box="[1066,1136,1392,1416]" name="Brazil" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFCBEFA7BC2E9FA7F" blockId="10.[810,1421,1451,1997]" box="[810,1214,1451,1476]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<taxonomicName id="E9F7AB85FFEEFFEFFCBEFA7BC2E9FA7F" authority="Linnaeus, 1758" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[810,1214,1451,1476]" class="Aves" family="Accipitridae" genus="Elanoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Accipitriformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="forficatus">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFCBEFA7BC2E9FA7F" bold="true" box="[810,1214,1451,1476]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" reason="1">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFCBEFA7BC25CFA78" bold="true" box="[810,1035,1451,1475]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Elanoides forficatus</emphasis>
Linnaeus, 1758
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFCBEFA03C5EBF9B7" blockId="10.[810,1421,1451,1997]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFCBEFA03C595FA50" bold="true" box="[810,962,1491,1515]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">New records.</emphasis>
Three individuals flying over PJDNR on 
<date id="5A49F6C6FFEEFFEFFCBEFA24C5EFF9B7" box="[810,952,1524,1548]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" value="2016-06-12">12 June 2016</date>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFCBEF9CAC29AF9CE" blockId="10.[810,1421,1451,1997]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFCBEF9CAC59BF989" bold="true" box="[810,972,1562,1586]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Identification.</emphasis>
The body is a contrast between deep black and white. The flight feathers, tail feet and bill are black. The tail is elongated and forked.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66ED838DFFEEFFEFFCBEF954C28BF83E" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFCBEF954C28BF83E" blockId="10.[810,1421,1451,1997]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFCBEF954C5CEF927" bold="true" box="[810,921,1668,1692]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Remarks.</emphasis>
We did not record any reproductive events. This species is a boreal migratory bird. We consider this species as an isolated record due to its unique record of three individuals. They could be wandering individuals of the subspecies 
<taxonomicName id="E9F7AB85FFEEFFEFFC65F8D9C535F8F9" authority="(Vieillot, 1818)" baseAuthorityName="Vieillot" baseAuthorityYear="1818" class="Aves" family="Accipitridae" genus="Elanoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Accipitriformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="forficatus" subSpecies="yetapa">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFC65F8D9C377F89A" box="[1009,1312,1801,1825]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Elanoides forficatus yetapa</emphasis>
(Vieillot, 1818
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFCCDF8FBC535F8F9" box="[857,866,1835,1858]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resident in 
<collectingCountry id="56E09096FFEEFFEFFC76F8FAC21DF8F9" box="[994,1098,1834,1858]" name="Colombia" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4A66ADF7FFEEFFEFFBCDF8FAC301F8F8" author="Ayerbe-Quinones F" box="[1113,1366,1834,1859]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" refId="ref12217" refString="Ayerbe-Quinones F (2018) Guia ilustrada de la avifauna colombiana. Wildlife Conservation Society, Bogota, 212 pp." type="book" year="2018">Ayerbe-Quiñones 2018</bibRefCitation>
), being recorded at a time when the migration of birds from the north of the continent was not usual.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66ED838DFFEEFFEFFCBEF843C23DF876" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2E48D006FFEEFFEFFCBEF843C23DF876" blockId="10.[810,1421,1451,1997]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">
<emphasis id="1C830C14FFEEFFEFFCBEF843C5E9F810" bold="true" box="[810,958,1939,1963]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Distribution.</emphasis>
Southeastern 
<collectingCountry id="56E09096FFEEFFEFFBC9F844C2C6F817" box="[1117,1169,1940,1964]" name="United States of America" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">USA</collectingCountry>
south through Central America and southern 
<collectingCountry id="56E09096FFEEFFEFFBB4F865C231F876" box="[1056,1126,1973,1997]" name="Brazil" pageId="10" pageNumber="1385">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
